Chapter 6: Factors using forcats (a core-tidyverse package)

Focuses on: (1) creating factor variables using factor(), (2) ordering data visualization based on numeric values ordering, (3) factor recoding, (4) lumping uncommon groups into Other.

# load tidyverse before continuing
library(tidyverse)

Factors

Factors are used for categorical variables.

Factors are useful when you want to display categorical variables using ordering that is not based on alphabetical order.

Example

An example where it would be nice to order months based on a specific ordering not based on alphabetical order:

monthly_sales <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jmtfeliciano/teachingdata/refs/heads/main/monthly_sales.csv")

monthly_sales |>
  arrange(month)
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    month        sales
##    <chr>        <dbl>
##  1 April     1107535.
##  2 August     935907.
##  3 December  1030058.
##  4 February   896802.
##  5 January    999424.
##  6 July       937372.
##  7 June       967210.
##  8 March     1010861.
##  9 May       1000537.
## 10 November   962693.
## 11 October   1090660.
## 12 September 1058530.

Currently, month is of character type and when you arrange this data by month, the orderingwhich is based on alphabetical orderdoesnt make sense in reality.

Converting variable into factor type

When your categorical variable (in this case, character/string) has an inherent order not based on alphabetical order, it is best you convert them into factor type to help enforce the ordering for printing data and in your data visualizations. You are able to indicate the proper order by specifying the levels of your data. For data visualization, the default ordering for character (strings) type is alphabetical order.

How to convert variable(s) into factor type

Step 1: Create a vector with the correct ordering or levels:

level_vector <- c("January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", 
                  "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December")

How to convert variable(s) into factor type

Step 2: Override variable by using mutate() and factor():

.tiny[

# levels or vector with the correct ordering
level_vector <- c("January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", 
                  "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December")

# How to use factor: 
# factor(variable_to_convert, levels = appropriate_levels)
monthly_sales_v2 <- monthly_sales |>
  mutate(month = factor(month, levels = level_vector))

]

One thing to note: month is no longer char (string). What variable type is now printed under month below?

# After converting month into factor, this should print the desired output:
monthly_sales_v2 |>
  arrange(month)
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    month        sales
##    <fct>        <dbl>
##  1 January    999424.
##  2 February   896802.
##  3 March     1010861.
##  4 April     1107535.
##  5 May       1000537.
##  6 June       967210.
##  7 July       937372.

Sample data

Summarizing data and creating data visualization

Suppose we are to calculate the average tv hours watched by religious group:

religion_tv_summary <- gss_cat |>
  group_by(relig) |>
  summarize(
    mean_tv_hours = mean(tvhours, na.rm = TRUE), n = n()
  )
religion_tv_summary

Creating data visualization: hours TV watched per religion

ggplot(data = religion_tv_summary,
       mapping = aes(x = mean_tv_hours, y = relig)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Mean Daily TV Hours Watched", y = "Religion")

Modify factor order in data visualization only

Suppose we are not happy with the last data visualization.

Instead of using the religion order given to us, suppose we want to modify the graph so that the order or levels are from most to least hours.

To do this, we can use fct_reorder(categorical_variable, numeric_variable_to_order_by).

Instead of y = relig, let us set y = fct_reorder(relig, mean_tv_hours).

Modify factor order in data visualization only

ggplot(data = religion_tv_summary,
       mapping = aes(x = mean_tv_hours, y = fct_reorder(relig, mean_tv_hours))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Mean Daily TV Hours Watched", y = "Religion")

Factor Recoding

Step 1: If variable is not a factor already, convert it first into factor type using factor().

Step 2: Use fct_recode(variable, {recoding map: new value = old value}).

flights_v2 <- flights |> 
  mutate(month = factor(month)) |>
  mutate(month = fct_recode(month,
                            "January" = "1",
                            "February" = "2",
                            "March" = "3",
                            "April" = "4",
                            "May" = "5",
                            "June" = "6",
                            "July" = "7",
                            "August" = "8",
                            "September" = "9",
                            "October" = "10",
                            "November" = "11",
                            "December" = "12"
                            ))

Lumping uncommon groupings into Other

fct_lump_min(variable, number_cut_off) allows us to reclassify groupings for uncommon factors or groupings as Other based on a numeric threshold or cut off.

For example, using fct_lump_n(species, 2) would only keep species designation if species count is 2 or more. In other words, species only appearing once is reclassified into Other.

starwars_v2 <- starwars |>
  mutate(species = fct_lump_min(species, 2))

head(starwars)
